    value: 未
english:
  title: A Letter Told in Dreams
  author: Kim Soo-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Recluse of Great Whiteness dwells in the dust of this world, yet his spirit wanders beyond all things. At times he wears the robes of the Confucian while following the Way of the Buddha. He drinks wine, yet fears becoming enslaved to it. He eats flesh, yet abhors the killing it requires.

    Seeking shelter from summer heat above a healing house south of Turtle Castle, he gazed down upon a fathomless pool. Within its depths swam fish called Silver-Mouth—countless as the grains of sand in the Ganges—some lurking in shadow, others dancing in the shallows, each dwelling in its proper place. On idle days, the recluse would tether his horse by the water's edge or plant his staff upon the bank, peering down with great joy. But one evening, as mountains and waters grew dark and wind and rain fell sharp and cold, the recluse grew weary. Supporting his chin upon his hand, he drifted into sleep—a state between form and formlessness, between presence and absence—when something stirred before him, lamenting and pleading, as if a subject come to petition his lord.

    "I am but a humble creature of the Water Kingdom," it spoke, "born humbly in the river lands below. Long have I heard of your lordship's benevolence, and I have journeyed far across a thousand li to reach these waters. Yet we need not have traveled so far. There are many streams where we might swim and hide—the Luo River east of Shang Mountain, the southern crossing of Zhu Mountain, the sand-channels of Xiang Valley. And should we journey upstream from our homeland, we can reach Sunheung in the north or Punggi to the west, where clear streams flow gently and white stones gleam beneath the surface, calling us with their sweetness.

    "But I confess, my lord, that though these other waters exist, I have been drawn irresistibly to this place. I have forsaken Sunheung and Punggi to remain here, and I do this for one reason alone: your lordship's heart is filled with compassion. You govern without harsh punishment. You cherish your people as a parent cherishes a child, and you love all creatures as you love your people. You forbid the herders from setting fires, so the insects and plants of the mountains and fields receive your mercy. You restrict the fishermen's nets, so the dragons and turtles and fish in every pond benefit from your grace.

    "Though necessity sometimes compels you to catch fish and turtles for tribute, you do so with restraint. Though you must hunt pheasant and rabbit to honor your guests, you do so with moderation. I have heard how once, when your procession briefly graced the riverside, you carefully selected small fish and returned them to the water, spreading your kindness to all creatures. Last year, when worthless men placed brushwood in the shallows to profit from the early frost, you commanded your officials to remove it all. Though listeners may laugh and onlookers may mock, I understand that your lordship's heart is steadfast in compassion, caring not for ridicule.

    "I have heard that the great prefect of Sunheung exchanges loyalty and righteousness with your lordship, that together you practice virtue and mutual encouragement, governing with pity and love for both people and creatures. For this reason, we water-folk cherish attachment to these lands and dare not leave. We wish only to dwell within your domain. Yet I have also heard rumors—that driven by courage and martial prowess, some harbor hidden malice and plot to destroy my family and overturn our dwelling. Such words bring us no joy but only terror. How strange that rumor speaks of virtue while the deeds contradict it, that what we once heard differs so from what we now witness!

    "Sunheung stands tall and magnificent, and its prefect's virtue shines brilliantly. Your lordship embodies the roots of refined culture and the very pulse of our age. Thus heaven and earth should entrust their care to you, and all creatures should rest in your heart. When others are endangered, you surely wish to bring them safety. When others face death, you surely wish to grant them life. How then could your lordship show me love while another seeks my harm? How could you nurture me while another plots my destruction?

    "Recently, my child, innocent and unknowing, ventured upstream and was captured. My liver and heart shattered into the waters below—I was seized with cold dread. Now this other sends letters proposing future meetings, offering heavy gifts and honeyed words, seeking our agreement. I have heard it said that 'the matter of conquering nations does not concern the virtuous person.' Yet perhaps your lordship's benevolence has not yet reached far enough, or perhaps your love for creatures has not yet moved the hearts of men? How else can such words fall so short of beauty?

    "I am but a humble creature, born in the depths of the sea, breathing in the river marshes. My birthplace is no legendary Bingxue cave, my breeding inferior to even the lowly Chatou fish. Among water-creatures, I am the smallest. Yet by grace of your lordship's compassion, I have come to dwell near your city, in proximity to the home of a cultivated gentleman. Above, I drink from clear streams; below, I shelter in shadowed valleys. Free from hook and line, liberated from nets, I pass my days in peace. How can I ever repay such boundless virtue?

    "Yet I fear your lordship lacks the iron resolve to resist pressure from greater powers. With one light word of agreement, evil guests may flock here, and my kind may be extinguished entirely. I am neither scaled fish nor armored creature; neither turtle nor shrimp—and yet strangely I appear to you in dreams. Did not ancient spirits commune with worthy men far beyond the land of Song alone?"

    The recluse stirred and awakened, wishing to understand these words, yet found no trace of their source. Only silver-mouthed fish, tens of thousands strong, moved in schools before him.

    Bowing, the recluse asked: "Was it not you who spoke to me so earnestly that night?"

    Ah, but fish are strange creatures, not human kind. Even among people, one cannot truly know another unless one becomes that person. How much less can I, a human, comprehend the nature of fish? Yet there is one among us practiced in writing and keen of mind. He has recorded this dream and shown it to me, the recluse. And so I share it now with those who, like Huizi at the bridge over the Hao, might appreciate its meaning.
  footnotes:
    - 'Bingxue (丙穴): A legendary cave where extraordinarily beautiful fish were said to originate, departing in spring and returning in autumn.'
    - 'Chatou (槎頭): A species of carp of inferior quality, used here as a reference point for humble origins.'
    - 'Huizi: The famous friend of Zhuangzi, known from their dialogue at the Hao Bridge about the nature of understanding and perspective—a fitting touchstone for a work about seeing through dreams.'
